 Copied from CZ's website:

 The CZ 75 SP-01 is the first full size handgun (4.61” bbl) from CZ to feature the improved manufacturing technology and ergonomics of the NATO-approved CZ 75 Compact P-01 model. Featuring an integral 1913 accessory rail on the dust cover, rubber grip panels, and CZ’s corrosion resistant black polycoat finish, the SP-01 is the newest model to join the family of pistols based on the CZ 75 (SA/DA) platform. Borrowing from the improved grip geometry of the compact P-01, the SP-01 utilizes an extended beavertail to protect shooter’s strong hand as well as allowing for a deeper and more secure grip. The new grip geometry, checkering in key areas on the front and back straps, and redistribution of mass provided by the accessory rail noticeably decrease the perceived recoil from previous models and allows for more rapid target acquisition and transition.

 The SP-01 was designed as a military and law enforcement duty sidearm. The new model is currently in use by security forces fighting the war on terrorism. Thanks to its exceptional accuracy and superior handling characteristics, the CZ 75 SP-01 has also found supporters in the field of sport and target shooting. Its list of users on the competition circuit include World Champions Adam Tyc and Angus Hobdell (1st and 3rd place respectively in 2005‘s IPSC championship, World Shoot XIV).

The barrel is a 1:9 twist WASP 5.56 NATO barrel. From CMMG's Website:
(Weapon Armament Surface Protection) is a salt bath ferritic nitrocarburizing surface conversion process or more commonly referred to as nitriding. The nitriding conversion is applied to the barrel inside and out, along with the front sight base on our LE rifles and uppers. Nitriding offers improved wear, abrasion, and corrosion resistance when compared to hard chrome lining or phosphating. 

Unlike chrome lining, where the chrome is built up on the surface, nitriding converts the surface without the risk of dimensional build up. CMMG Pioneered the use of this nitriding process on AR barrels and has been using it for many years.

This upper has fired every round put through it. Has standard wear with use.

title: For Sale:  Walther P-38 nickeled (!)
location: Santa Fe, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
Pictures tell most of the story but not all. This is  a 1942 Walther P-38 made by Spreewerke with the "cyq" code markings. Serial numbers all match.  It is a superb shooter, and has had the feedramp polish so it will feed hardball and hollowpoint 9mm reliably. I regularly shoot empty shotgun shells  at 25 yards with it. After WWII, many of these GI bringbacks were nickeled since at the time they were not expensive and to 1940s and '50s eyes they were "prettier" in nickel. One thing about nickel is that it is tough, so the condition of the gun is really nice. All markings are there, including the Waffenampt (eagle/swastika) acceptance marks. When I got it, the seller told me it fed just fine. Well, let's just say he was optimistic. So I polished the feed ramp, cleaned and lubed it, and it now runs 100%. Bore is great, and it is accurate.  I am only selling it because I would like to buy a weird Swiss rifle. (If you have a really nice K31, let's talk, lol.)

I have it in a nice little case I put together to keep it from getting scratched,  since it is in great refinished condition. It comes with  one nickeled magazine,  one brand new P1/P38 magazine, and a superb reproduction 1942 P38 holster. These are all pictured. It also comes with the original brown WWII grips, but I thought this shiny nickeled gun was crying for some ivory grips, so I had a set of faux ivories made for it and aged appropriately. All in all, it came out pretty nice I think.

There are NO importer's markings on it, thank goodness. 

At any rate, if you want to be anonymous at the shooting range, this gun is not for you. But, if you would like something that has a bit of history, is reliable, accurate; and fun to look at and shoot, this may be something you will enjoy. Basically,  if you like '59 Cadillacs, this is your gun. Not just fun though. This is also a serious 9mm German fighting pistol.

If you want to have a look at it in person, contact me through Armslist with your email and phone number and we can meet up. I think you will like my gun when you see it. I know you will like it when you shoot it. Plus best of all, it is a practical piece of history, yet still cheaper than most of the plastic guns out there. Funny, it looks a lot like the $5,000 one on Gunbroker, lol. Check that one out.

Thanks for reading my VERY long-winded ad! 
Doby Pilgrim
Santa Fe
